    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_484537704" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/484537704" />
    <a title="Leif" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2558741-leif"><img alt="Leif" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1369506326p2/2558741.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/484537704?book_show_action=true">Dec 24, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Leif" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Leif" href="/user/show/2558741-leif">Leif</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer484537704" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14270523395575589736">Christopher Priest&apos;s <i>The Glamour</i> is a staggering and self-referential spiral that devours itself, producing a series of disorienting narrative shifts in vision, imagination, and ultimately knowledge. A number of stories are effectively told (of which Susan&apos;s perhaps the most compelling). The cumulative influence of the novel is chilling for its more-than-a-touch bitter nature, but along the way there is plenty of compelling material here.<br/><br/><blockquote>We all make fictions. Not one of us is what we seem. When </blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText14270523395575589736" style="display:none">Christopher Priest's <i>The Glamour</i> is a staggering and self-referential spiral that devours itself, producing a series of disorienting narrative shifts in vision, imagination, and ultimately knowledge. A number of stories are effectively told (of which Susan's perhaps the most compelling). The cumulative influence of the novel is chilling for its more-than-a-touch bitter nature, but along the way there is plenty of compelling material here.<br /><br /><blockquote>We all make fictions. Not one of us is what we seem. When we meet other people we try to project an image of ourselves that will please or influence them in some way. When we fall in love we blind ourselves to what we do not wish to see. We wear certain clothes, drive particular cars, live in certain areas, all to project an image of ourselves. We sift through our memories not to understand the past, but to suit our present understanding of ourselves. (234)</blockquote><br />Ultimately, Priest's novel is perhaps too wrapped up in the phantasm (the fantastic image), too taken for the images understood as reality to see the undergirding structure of material life. Life alone is not glamourous enough, and so the unwinding and mirror-like stories the novel tells effectively provide layers of competing narrative meaning overtop. Perhaps, as Italian philosopher Giorgio Agamben writes, we live in a time when "the real world is transformed into an image and images become real" and in this mirrorshade transformation "the practical power of humans is separated itself and presented as a world unto itself" (<i>The Coming Community</i>, 79). If this is in fact true then the glamour of Priest's chilling vision is one more acute reflection on the simulacrum we create---but it is one that does not touch our experience of reality. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14270523395575589736" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

