        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1083769736" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6616986209601523751">The more Priest one reads, obviously, the more themes and narrative devices start to repeat -- I&apos;ll admit I rolled my eyes a bit when it became clear that this was doing *both* the split-universe thing from <i>The Separation</i> *and* the mobius-strip narrative of <i>The Affirmation</i> -- but Priest&apos;s imagination is so fertile and his writing so gripping that it kind of doesn&apos;t matter. Of the Priest novels I&apos;ve made it through, this is actually the one where his trademark ambiguity seems the most productive,</span>
  <span id="freeText6616986209601523751" style="display:none">The more Priest one reads, obviously, the more themes and narrative devices start to repeat -- I'll admit I rolled my eyes a bit when it became clear that this was doing *both* the split-universe thing from <i>The Separation</i> *and* the mobius-strip narrative of <i>The Affirmation</i> -- but Priest's imagination is so fertile and his writing so gripping that it kind of doesn't matter. Of the Priest novels I've made it through, this is actually the one where his trademark ambiguity seems the most productive, since it connects directly to the book's main plot hook.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6616986209601523751" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

